    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-16T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-16T19:00:00-05:00" n="431"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d431">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 (D) Regulations/2313: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-16T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 16, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:04 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. Reference Department’s telegram no. 98, May 15, noon.<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d431fn49">Not printed.</note> The Minister of Finance<note n="50"
                        xml:id="d431fn50">David Dasso.</note> stated today that the matter must be
                    submitted to the Cabinet for consideration and an official reply is not expected
                    before the end of next week. Informally he said that Peru hesitated to impose a
                    prohibition of exports of domestic products, particularly where contracts had
                    been made for future deliveries. Furthermore, he said that he did not wish to
                    make Peru the spearhead in the imposition of such drastic restrictions for fear
                    of international complications and that he would prefer to see at least four or
                    five of the other American Republics announce such a decision about the same
                    time.</p>
                <p>With respect to the prohibition of the reexportation of products on United States
                    export license list the Minister said that there should be no difficulty in this
                    respect inasmuch as no international question is involved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
